Center: Center of Nuclear Physics Data, Russian Federal Nuclear Center (VNIIEF), Sarov, Russia
ref: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.223, p.351 (1974)
title: Direct processes in the 6Li(a,d)8Be reaction.

x4freetext: Direct processes in the 6Li(a,d)8Be reaction.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.223, p.351 (1974)

x4freetext: A  dE-E telescope consisting of two silicon
detectors 10-50 mu-m and 1 mm thick, respectively. The
telescope used to detect particles emitted backwards
with energies below 5 MeV was located inside the
scattering chamber. Particles with greater energies
passed through a slit sealed by a thin (10 mu-m) mylar
film and were detected by a telescope mounted outside
the scattering chamber. Thus it was possible to place
in front of the detectors various aluminium foils of
the required thickness to absorb a great number of
alpha particles scattered at small angles.
The targets, which were 0.3 to 0.4 mg/cm2 thick, were
made by vacuum evaporation of lithium carbonate,
enriched in 6Li to 92%, onto a silver or gold backing
0.25 mg/cm2 thick. The target was placed at the centre
of a 18 cm diameter scattering chamber at a distance
of 90 cm from the foils.
The beam energy was varied by means of stopping
aluminium foils 5.65 mu-m thick.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: Absolute cross section error. The
accuracy of the absolute values is mainly due to the
accuracy of measurement of the target thickness and the
uncertainty of the target composition because of the
possible disintegration of lithium carbonate when the
target is heated by an alpha particle beam.
The statistical errors of the differential cross
sections for the 6Li(a,d)8Be reaction mostly did not
exceed 10%. The cross sections for the d1 group were
measured somewhat less accurately (~15%) since this
group occurs against the background of the continuous
spectrum of deuterons from the 6Li(a,ad)4He and
6Li(a,a)6Li* -> a+d reactions.
